<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written Evidence Submitted by POhWER</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written Evidence </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">from</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">POhWER</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> [PHS0042]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This submission is made by POhWER, an advocacy charity established over fifteen years ago by service users who felt unequal to the task of voicing concerns about decisions made by public bodies on matters that affected their day to day lives.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We provide NHS complaints advocacy services from the outset. We focus particularly on people who are vulnerable, distressed or drawn from the protected equality groups.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Last year alone, we handled over 30,000 calls about the NHS complaints process to our information, advice and advocacy centre and provided over 4,000 people with direct advocacy support. We can draw on the experiences of all these clients to provide you with evidence based views on the Parliamentary and Health Service </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Ombudsman</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Our focus in this submission is on the second tier of the NHS complaints handling process. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he first tier </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">was designed with substantial complainant involvement and feedback from our clients suggests that it has the potential to deliver the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">kind of approach and the outcomes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">they seek. However, it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">suffers from poor implementation and has not kept pace with the recent NHS changes. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Unfortunately our experience with the second tier, when cases are taken to the Ombudsman, is not so positive. This is particularly worrying in an organisation that is a specialist complaint handler.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">So far this year, since April 2013, 8% of our NHS cases were referred on to the Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman (PHSO). In previous years, we have referred around 15% of cases to PHSO.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> The reason for this seems</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to be a growing reluctance to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">use the Ombudsman service because of the experiences of others.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Our clients tell us that they have experienced the following problems:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Delay</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> understand that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in April 2013, PHSO changed its complaints process in order to be able to investigate more complaints. It also changed its senior management structure and is soon to make </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">significant </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">changes to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">resources in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the structure below</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that level</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. The impact of the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">se changes for our clients appears to have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">been to lengthen the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">complaints </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">process</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and make it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">less customer focused</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e understand that there are over 700 complaints being held in a backlog before a decision to investigate is even made.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> One client has been informed that PHSO will take 40 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">days</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> just</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to consider whether to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">investigate their complaint which mean</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s it will be mid-January before </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">our client will hear from PHSO again. This is a long time for a client to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">know whether their case is even going to be considered, let alone resolved. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">And if they are not being communicated with during the process</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (see below)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, it can become extremely frustrating and upsetting for our clients.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Poor service and bias in favour of bodies complained about</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">lients tell their us that c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">omplaints </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">are being </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">paraphrased rather than</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> conveyed to organisations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> ‘as put’ by the complainant:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> PHSO’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">interim casework policy and guidance – section 4: Proposals to investigate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> states that they scope what they are (and are not) proposing to investigate and that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> decision to narrow the scope of the complaint </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that has been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">put to them is theirs. Our clients are reporting to us that this means that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> all too often</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">PHSO does not address</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he issues they wanted consider</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ed. C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ertain aspects </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are ignored and others are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">interpreted wrongly or not stated clearly. In one case where our client objected to the summary of her complaint, her case was ‘withdrawn’ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by PHSO </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as she would not consent for her truncated complaint to be sent to the Trust as her complaint.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> This</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> appears to run against </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> intention of the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Health Service Ombudsman Act </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">which states:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:14.4pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Procedure in respect of investigations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">.</span><span style="background-color:#660066; color:#ffffff; display:none; font-family:Arial; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">E+W+S+N.I.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:18pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">(1)Where a Commissioner proposes to conduct an investigation pursuant to a complaint under </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; font-weight:bold">[</span><a href="http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1993/46/section/11#commentary-c1249131"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-weight:bold">F1</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">section 3(1)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12.5pt; font-weight:bold">]</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">, he shall afford— </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:18pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">(a)to the health service body concerned, and </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:18pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">(b)to any other person who is alleged in the complaint to have taken or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">authorised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> the action complained of, </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:18pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">an opportunity to comment on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">any allegations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> contained in the complaint. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:18pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-3.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This surely means that PHSO should not paraphrase</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the meaning of a complaint or reduce it to what they think t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hey can achieve.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">At the very least they need to explain to complainants why they feel no worthwhile outcome can be obtained on the aspects that they propose not to investigate so that complainants have a chance to challenge this.  By the time they have reached the Ombudsman, most complainants are battle weary. They would not be pursuing the case if they did not feel a strong sense of injustice.  The Ombudsman is their last hope –  surely incumbent on her to do her best to investigate or explain fully why she feels there is nothing useful to be achieved.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Lack of openness with the complainant</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">: clients tell us that documents that form part of the investigation are shared</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> only </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with bodies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> complained about</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. As a result, complainants cannot confirm whether the information from the body is correct or complete. The impact of this is that complainants feel the process is biased towards the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">organisation complained about</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and that their views are insignificant </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the whole process.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">10</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Poor communication</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> many of our clients tell us that they are only contacted at the beginning and end of the process but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">not on an on going </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">basis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. Therefore, they have no idea about the progress of their complaint, nor are they given an opportunity to clarify or comment on the responses received by the body until the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">draft report is written. T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">his is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">usually </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">too late as the Ombudsman is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">frequently</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> unwilling to accept new information or evidence at this stage.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">11</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Lack of integration: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">many of our client’s complaints </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cross the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> health and social care </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">boundaries</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. PHSO does not have the remit to investigate social care complaints and therefore our clients then either need to deal with two Ombudsmen or have their complaint investigated as a ‘joint investigation’. As the two Ombudsmen sit in different locations, have different processes and different remits, this makes it very difficult for our clients and all the problems stated above are exacerbated.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">12</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Lack of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">mpact:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">PHSO’s own figures show </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that, in 2012-2013, they received over 24,000 complaints about the NHS or Government departments. Of these, they completed 384 investigations which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">was</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> less than 2% of all complaints received. Therefore, the learning from complaints is limited to a relatively small number of complaints and the impact is minimised.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As noted earlier, this poor level of impact is a key factor in clients ’decisions not to take their case to PHSO. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">PHSO and Advocacy</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">13</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Our experience shows that advice and advocacy services provide an important and independent link between the service provider and the client. We provide our clients with the confidence and tools to voice their concerns and to ensure improvements are made as a result. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">14</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Advocacy and advice can support a complainant, help PHSO with its communication and ensure that the process is balanced and fair. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We believe PHSO could benefit from creating stronger links with advice and advocacy providers </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">who are trained in this field. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A survey conducted by PHSO in 2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">011 and shared with ICAS providers showed that of all the advice and advocacy organisations they surveyed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> knowledge of PHSO and a good understanding of the service it provided was very significantly higher</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in the NHS complaints advocacy service</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> than in other advice and advocacy agencies. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Furthermore, the take up rate for health cases supported by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">specialist NHS complaints advocates</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is three times that of the general PHSO take up rate. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">15</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Currently PHSO provides a link on its website to an organisation calling itself ‘NHS Advocacy Services’. Not only is this link b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uried in the site and fails to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> appear when you search the site using the term ‘advocacy’, it also links to only one </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">advocacy provider</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> cover</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s only a limited part </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of England. This discriminates against vulnerable clients in all other geographical areas and causes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">confusion for the complainant as there is no signposting to providers in their area. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> We have also not been able to meet with the Ombudsman in over a year to discuss how we can work together for the benefit of complainant</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What would make PHSO better?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">16</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We feel that PHSO </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">would benefit from</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the following.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">17</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Being more customer focused. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t POhWER</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> we ensure we contact our clients on a regular basis, to keep them updated and to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ensure they clearly understand what is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">happening</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. We also ensure that there is complete transparency and share documentation with our clients whenever possible.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> PHSO would be better if it improved its communication and openness with complainants.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">18</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Having an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">external review of its processes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">urrently </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">PHSO’s process</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> appears to have lengthened the time to investigate, introduced more delays for customers, shows bias towards the body complained about and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">does not investigate the complaint as stated</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">An external review of PHSO’s new process</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, perhaps involving complainants,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and determining whether it is actually bringing any benefits to complainants or delivering value for money would be beneficial.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">19</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Having an integrated approach to health and social care complaints. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">single health and social care investigation process which is clearly signposted and consistent across the boundaries</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, mirroring the process at tier 1 would be far more efficient than the current arrangements.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">20</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Making better use of advice and advocacy services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">, and doing more to support vulnerable people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Engaging more with advice and advocacy services and better signposting to these providers on their website</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> would benefit PHSO, the body being investigated and the complainant and give everyone</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> – and especially vulnerable people - </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">an opportunity to make their voice heard.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> This would also reflect the recognition afforded to advocacy support in the Francis Report, the Government’s response and the Clwyd Hart Review.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  PHSO might also wish to reflect on the lack of advocacy support for people with Parliamentary complaints.  Many of these complainants are drawn from the most vulnerable and distressed populations in the country and the absence of active lobbying for support for their needs (despite evidence of the effectiveness of advocacy).</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">21</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Having a regional presence rather than a national </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">focus</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As the NHS has changed and there is a greater emphasis on regional or local knowledge, PHSO would benefit from regional </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">investigators, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with greater knowledge and awareness of issues in their area.  This would grow the expertise of the investigators of the bodies within their area and they would be more likely to spot the systemic issues arising on a regional basis than a national one.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">22</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We hope that the Select Committee finds this information </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of use for its inquiry into the Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman. There is a great deal more we can say and would be very pleased to assist in any way we can.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>